            "abstractNote": "The Messel Pit Fossil Site (a UNESCO World Heritage Site) is located within the Sprendlingen Horst (SW Germany), a basement unit forming the northeastern shoulder of the Upper Rhine graben. The Messel Pit is interpreted as an isolated lake sediment occurrence created by phreatomagmatic activity. 4OAr/39Ar dating with stepwise heating via laser on a redeposited basalt fragment within a lapilli tuff recovered by the Messel research drilling of2001 yields a plateau age of 47.8 ± 0. 2 Ma (Middle Eocene). This age correlates with a major phase of volcanic activity in the Sprendlingen Horst during the short time span from 49 to 47 Ma. The 4OAr/39Ar date enables a numerical calibration of the Messel lake sedimentation. The contemporaneously deposited taphocoenosis corresponds to the marnmalian biostratigraphic reference level Mammal Paleogene MP 11. For phreatomagmatic activity associated with the maar crater collapse and contemporaneous onset of lake sedimentation, an age of 48 Ma might be derived. Frequency analyses along with sedimentol ogical criteria point to a subsequent phase of sedimentation lasting approximately 1 Ma. The age of the fossils excavated thus far from the uppermost part of the Messel sediments could thus be 47 Ma. Correspondingly, an estimate for the MP II time interval is 47.5 to 46.5 Ma. Since MP II represents the base ofEuropean Land Mammal Age (ELMA) Geiseltalian, the boundary with the older ELMA Grauvian can be estimated at 47.5 Ma.",
